<Review>I've been coming and going here for years. Plenty of parking and easy pick-up and drop-offs in front of the historic station. There are two sets of bathrooms and a vending machine inside the building (no coffee but a Starbucks a short walk away).

The station itself is for Amtrak trains  -- Metrolink trains stop some yards further north. It has always been a safe and clean public space, but lately (and inevitably) homeless people have begun hanging out there, littering and stinking up up the waiting room as they mutter and giggle to themselves. There are guards who patrol the grounds but they either can't or won't do anything to keep them away. Ditto the police, so far.

A sign of the times.

Edit: It has gotten much better since I posted the above comment earlier this year. The persistent homeless and their litter are gone, at least as of May, 2021.</Review><userid>116170771368555703306<//userid><pics>None< /pics>< GmapID>
0x80c2c0de464f3787:0x71e6b0e28df29d99</GmapID>

<rate>5<//rate>< text>
This is my second time here. The first time i was completely blown away at how perfectly Ray and Sandys Hideaway fit the profile of a dive bar. As me and my date read reviews of the bar while sitting at the bar, we could not hold in our outbursts of laughter.
I ordered a bottle of coors lite and my date ordered a shot of Jager ( totaled less than $10) as my date took shot after shot, so did our petite and beautiful Bartender.
You basically need scuba gear because this a deep sea dive bar. There is no security ( unless you count the tiny female bartender or regular custys that might jump in to stop fights)
The kitchen is located directly in the bar( btw the bartender is also the cook)
The best part is the Decor! As you walk in you see outdated beer promotions all over the walls which are wood on one side and brick on the other. The owner has a very "tasteful" velvet nude painting of herself that favors the classic Jesus with Thorns paintings you can find in most pisa grandma houses along with their plastic covered couches located next to the Bitchen (Bar and Kitchen)
The ceiling tiles are artistic with what i assume to be personal peices of art work from regular customers. Consider it the dive bar Sistine Chapel.
I could go on and on but i conclude with giving this bar 5 stars. If you want to get drunk, sing and hear bad kareoke in your pajamas this is the place to go. I Love It. Cheap Drinks, Bad food, Drunk Staff and Guarenteed STDs if you sit on their toilet seats... Our Kinda Place ( Dont sit, Squat)<//text>

<username>Michael Kirrene< /username><time>1487617084220< /time><rate>5< /rate>< Text>
The chef at Tanaka takes pride in every dish he presents. Each dish is beautifully presented on white plates which gives focuses the presentation on the fish.  The fish is extraordinarily fresh and the chef highlights each piece with different salts, fresh yuzu, fresh wasabi, and light citrus sauces. I recommend the omakase... And for this kind of quality at this price you can't find anywhere. The service is very pleasant and attentive. Never intrusive but always aware of the tables and your needs. If you are looking for soy sauce and special rolls go else where. But if you are looking for artisticly presented, fresh fish in a quiet, low key setting I highly recommend Tanaka Sushi.</Text>

<Name>Chester Lin</Name>< date>
1512714721206<//date>
<Rating>5</Rating><review>Words cannot describe how good the sushi is here. You'll be amazed and puzzled. You'll find yourself asking... Am I really in a Simi valley strip mall? What is this fish? Where does one get it? Gingko fish, sea robin...

How do you get salmon to be this soft and flavorful yet carry the flavor of charred salmon skin? How can the Toro be as tender as the uni? What is this sea perch that is fresh like white fish yet melts in your mouth like fatty red fish?

You'll also meet fun and charming people sitting along with you at the sushi bar. They are probably regulars who love sushi and love the place. It's like sitting at the theater with fellow fans. Their enjoyment adds to yours.

Chef's menu changes frequently and each visit I'm surprised at the inventiveness, thoughtfulness and of course deliciousness that he brings to the table. Add to it a very well curated and well priced sake list and it's a place worthy of any special occasion. And one that I want to come to all the time.< /review>< pics>

< Review>
This is truly a Japanese sushi restaurant. I was a little disoriented because I뗤 used to the Americanized sushi restaurants. I can뗪 believe how authentic and amazing this place is and ESPECIALLY in Simi Valley! I뗬e been to several sushi restaurants that were 랊k but this place simply blew them out of the water. They get their fish almost daily from a fish market that imports directly from Japan. The taste will tell you all you need to know. Beware: place is small so make reservations to ensure a seat.<//Review>

Sushi Master Psy infuses a touch of Meditteranian Truffle Olive Oil with a lime or lemon clear Sause over delicate pieces of Japanese Sushi.  Uses a nice torch flamed charcoal for flavoring certain fish. The Crispy Fried Shrimp head with shrimp sushi with Caviar, fresh Black Truffle chips and 24k gold flakes is to die for.  Very pricey $$$$. Reservation is key.  Sits 7 people at the bar and about 6 people between 3 small tables.</Text>

<username>Shant Joukjian<//username><resp>None< /resp>< pictures>
None< /pictures>
<Text>I mean, wow. If you want some of the highest quality, traditional style sushi straight from Japan, this is the place to come. I travel all around looking for the freshest fish and authentic style of serving sushi and this check marks every box. The chef is from Japan and clearly has been trained in the art of fine sushi. His fish is top notch , the service is impeccable and the level of detail he put to each piece of nigiri is exceptional. Don't expect stupid saucy Americanized rolls and soy sauce platters to drench rolls into. He glazes each fish with its own sauce to compliment that specific fish. It's a small little place, very clean and organized. Let the chef do his thing and take his omakase course if your new to this type of sushi. Otherwise go down that nigiri list and enjoy yourself. This place is a hidden gem and I will definitely be going back soon.</Text></record>

<UserId.>111288791206518349972< /UserId.>< review>
I love this place. So, I left this same lengthy review on Yelp. This has to be the rarest gem in Simi Valley. If you are looking for authentic sushi and outstanding service, this is the place to be. The restaurant itself is situated next to a hair salon and doesn't look anything out of the ordinary from the outside. Don't be fooled! The inside was elegant, quiet, charming, and very clean. We sat at the bar and ordered the $100 Omakase meal per person. Totally worth every penny and all 15 dishes. The sushi chef had exemplary skills and attention to detail. Each dish we ordered was so delicious and presented so well. You can tell that he had knife skills with the precision he had with the cuts on the fish and how he prepared everything.

You must drink with sake when you come here,  it will make your dinner even more enjoyable. The vibe was very relaxing in the restaurant. Limited seating so it's best to make reservations in advance.

I came here for my birthday on October 14 and I was shocked when the lovely waitress came up next to me with a sweet "Happy Birthday!" and handed me a plate of what I believe were the best tasting ice cream mochi Ive had by far. And I have had a lot of Mochi Ice cream before . Most Japanese restaurants seem to just serve the store bought ones. This, however, was the real deal. The mochi dough was melt-in-your-mouth delicious! The vanilla ice cream inside was so smooth and creamy, almost as if they just made it. They even added a birthday candle on one. I wasn't expecting that since I dont think I've ever had a birthday mochi before. It was so simple and perfect.

All I have left to say is, DEFINITELY give this place a try because it's totally worth checking out.

I will be coming back for sure.<//review>

I'd give them 0 stars if I could honestly. We purchased an air conditioner unit from them around 2011 with a warranty that extends into approximately 2022. First Arctic Air didn't install the unit correctly which cause water damage to our roof after some rainstorms passed by. After having people inspect the roof we had another local air conditioner company inspect the unit and tell Arctic Air how it was installed incorrectly. Later on after many complaints of one of our rooms not receiving enough cold air, Arctic Air thought it was a great idea to install a new vent that requires a filter 11 and 1/2 feet in the air on the roof of the tallest room in our house. However where the company really shined was this summer when the unit broke down. After waiting for hours for their serviceman to show up and take a look at the unit they informed us that the parts they needed were not available on weekends through our warranty and that we would either have to wait until the following Monday to get the parts through our warranty cause the place they get them from was already closed because it was Friday. However they "generously" offered to get the part for us the following morning if we paid them 350 dollars for it. We opted to get a second opinion on the unit after hearing the unfair price and ultimately decided to pay the 350. The next day they showed up, fixed the unit and charged us 750 dollars instead. Take my advice, don't call this company and forget they even exist. Take your money elsewhere.</text>

< text>
Crooked Dealership....Beware!

I would think twice before doing business with Piercey Toyota. They won't tell you the price online, at least for the Toyota Supra, even though literally every other Toyota dealership I emailed did. Instead, they tell you that you need to come in and discuss it there in person. For those that don't know, this is a major red flag, and reason enough to shop elsewhere. Not to mention the optics of forcing people to stop by in person, while we are still in the midst of the pandemic.

I just feel bad for the people that don't know any better, and will end up walking in there, only to be scammed by people like Ky Nguyen, the Internet Sales Manager.< /text>

Great experience here.  I started off emailing Mike Sheard at Piercy a few months ago and he always answered my millions of questions.  After finding the Lunar Rock rav4 that we wanted we went to the showroom and let me tell you this Dealership in Milpitas is huge. My experience at Piercey Toyota was great.
I was thinking of buying a new car starting the end of 2019. It took me some time to think which model I will buy. I requested a quote through Costco car sale program and some other websites after I made my mind to buy the Prius Prime. Of course, I started to receive emails from several dealers after I requested the quote. Among these dealers, Pari Juergens, the Fleet Manager from Piercey Toyota, might be the first person who contacted me. She called me directly and asked my needs, also scheduled an appointment right away. Yes, she is very efficient comparing to some other dealers.
Later, I went to meet her and she showed me the cars I am interested and explained the differences between Prius and Prius Prime, Prius Prime 2019 vs 2020. She also answered many my questions patiently, which was important for me to make my final decision.
In that same weekend, I visited Piercey Toyota again and came back with my dream car, Titanium 2020 Prius Prime. I am very grateful that all the processing had been very smooth with all the help from each person involved. It was a great experience.
Pari also called me later to know my experiences in driving my new car and again she answered several my questions.
I am so happy to have my new car. Just could not stop loving it. Thank you, Piercey Toyota! Thank you. Pari!</text>

I had a rear axle seal give way due to a previous Toyota dealer not tightening a wheels lugs at ALL!

I paid 1500.00 to drive away in a vehicle that has 346000 miles, in a worse shape than it came in.

< review>
I made an appointment for my 2012 Toyota Camry's 90,000 mile service.  Mike Tran did a good job of explaining what the car needed.  The waiting area is very nice with tables that I like to use to catch up on work.  There is also good coffee choices and hot chocolate!    In addition to the normal oil change and tire rotation, they also put in new coolant, brake fluid, transmission fluid and an air filter.  Their multi-point check identified and replaced a burned out brake light, which I did not know about. When the  service was completed,  a video from the technician was provided. He estimated that I might need new brakes with my next service.  The staff at Piercey Toyota is always very professional.  I have purchased two vehicles from them - a 2000 Celica that ran for 315,000 miles before I replaced it with my 2012 Camry that had 26,400 miles on it in 2015 when I bought it. So I have been a Piercey customer for almost 20 years.  They have done all of the service and maintenance on my cars.  Thank you, Mike Tran for being a good partner in keeping me and my Camry safely on the road!<//review>

<Response>None</Response><Review>I previously rated the service department with five stars.  Unfortunately I'm only able to post one review so I had to downgrade the rating to one star, that they still don't deserve, in order to address our issues with the sales department.

Last October we went in to pick up a Toyota Camry my husband arranged to be held.  When we arrived, there were four salesmen leaning on the driver side of the car lolly-gagging when we pulled up.  This was the first issue.  My husband addressed his disappointment with Mike, the salesman we did business with and the sales manager later came to apologize and offered to ensure the car was detailed well- this should have been the condition of delivery anyway.

Secondly, we expressed that we were paying for the car in full and therefore there was no reason to run our credit.  Mike assured us that they would only run a soft credit report, but that wasn't the case.  Unfortunately he's not knowledgeable of the process his finance department uses, but as of this date he should be.  My husband and I immediately received notifications from Credit Karma that a hard credit inquiry had been added to our reports. When we addressed it with Mike he was adamant that it would come off in two weeks.  Again, he is not knowledgable of this process at all.  He said he'd make sure this was fixed, but after the sale of the car he wasn't responsive to text or phone calls.  Imagine that.

Thirdly, after purchasing the car we did not receive the maintenance or instruction manuals with the car.  My husband later went by to pick up the manuals and received 2019 manuals for a 2018 Camry.  Again, they were adamant that they were the same.  When we compared them to our Camry, they were not the same.  Again, another indication of the lack of knowledge of this sales department.

Lastly, we just happened to be moving two weeks after the purchase of the vehicle and therefore needed the dealership to update our address with the DMV to ensure the title came to the right address.  They told us it was our responsibility to do so.  Unbeknownst to them we had already  went to the DMV and attempted to do this, but the DMV confirmed that only the dealer could do this.  My husband relayed the information to the sales department and again they were adamant they could not do it.

So, my husband contacted Toyota Headquarters to submit a complaint about all of the above.  The headquarter's customer service department took the complaint with disappointment that we had been treated in the manner we had.  I later received a call from Piercey's customer relation manager, who followed up with the complaint submitted.

Long story short, the customer relation's manager remained content that they had done everything they could.  When I threatened them with legal implications she responded that they had an attorney that represented them too...as if, I was naive to the fact.  They're a business, they should have some form a liability protection.  After our last conversation, my husband communicated the outcome to Toyota headquarter's.  We later received a call from the customer relations manager accompanied by another manager on the phone.  After all was said and done, we have received the correct manuals for our Camry, the title came to the correct address and they sent a letter to the three credit bureaus.

Unfortunately, as anyone who has ever dealt with trying to resolve any type of credit dispute with the Big Three,  it has cost us unnecessary time and headaches in trying to get that credit inquiry off our report. However, it was worth ever bit of my time writing this review as they have caused a waste of my time that I'll never get back.  This is the worst experience we've ever had with a Toyota dealership and we've been loyal Toyota owners since 2002.  If you're considering purchasing Toyota in the Bay Area- consider "all" your options.  Piercey Toyota should not be one of them.<//Review><Gmap_id>0x808fc9305c5f88bd:0x17594267a9346d1d< /Gmap_id>< Rate>

<Rating>1<//Rating><text>Took my mothers 08' Camry in for a recall regarding excessive oil consumption. We then get a phone call from the service department stating that the engine was leaking from the valve cover gaskets, oil pan, water pump and the coolant was low. Also, the battery was leaking acid. A good chunk of $$ for repairs, but within reason. The recall inspection couldn't be completed until these leaks were first addressed since there's no way to detect excessive oil usage if the engine leaks. I declined repairs through them, as I manage an auto repair facility and could have my *ASE certified* technicians inspect and fix the issues. Picked up the vehicle and brought it to my shop. Upon having not one, not two, but THREE technicians, and also myself inspect for leaks and everything else, we found NONE. Can you imagine that? NO leaks! It was bone dry! Coolant was just fine. The battery did absolutely need to be replaced. They got that right.

I know in the dealer world, technicians get paid flat rate. And if it's a slow day, it means paycheck won't be looking too good. So I'm sure they find "work" that has to be done. This is completely unfair to consumers! And this is also what gives good and honest technicians a bad rep. I have considered filing a complaint with the B.A.R.

In conclusion, I have taken the vehicle to another Toyota dealer and they also didn't confirm any leaks. How funny is that?

< Review>
Piercey Toyota is one of the best Toyota dealerships out there. Their location is super convenient to most North SJ office locations. They have shuttle services in addition to loaners.

On my recent 30k service for my Prius, I was pleasantly surprised when I got a text message with a video from the technician who was servicing my car. The technician had my car up on the lift and walked me through things he was performing as part of the service. It was a full 2 min explanation straight from the technician. This is an awesome feature in itself that I have not seen anywhere else.

The lounge is comfortable both to relax or work (good quality wifi). There are snacks, coffee, water and clean restrooms. Everyone from the service reception to the coordinator, technicians, parts department and cashier checkout are respectful and very service oriented.

Highly recommend this dealership (and Toyota of course!)</Review>

< review>
I have very good experience with the car service department. I specifically want to mention and thank Miss Diana Conzalez and Mr. Mike Jiminez. This is what happened that prompted me to write this review: Diana misquoted a promotion price on a set of tires because she genuinely thought that there is a promotion going (which has just expired). I did not pay much attention and just put my initial at the actual price that is printed out without the promotion. Later I found out that this is wrong and I was overcharged. Most other dealers would just said that hey you agree on this when you put your initial, so it is your problem and the promotion is indeed over, there is nothing much that they can do. They are perfectly justified to say that. But Diana and Mike went the extra mile to fix it me and still honor the promotion. I could not be happier. I don't generally do reviews, but I feel I need to tell others about their excellent service.

Of course the actual car servicing work performed by the mechanics there is great. I have been going there for 3+ years and never have any problem. Highly recommend this place.< /review>

< review>
Experience is defined by a situation which is out of normal.
Recently I had a flat tyre after I got back from a vacation. Piercey being the nearest dealer, I contacted them for the repair. However there was no appointment available until the following Monday (5 days forward). I explained them that it's difficult to wait that long since I have just 1 car and I have a 1 young toddler. However I kept getting repetitive response from representative as if I was speaking to a non-human recorded machine without any emotions. On again requesting for a drop-in appointment, I was asked to call on Friday morning 7 am. I kept calling from 7 am - 8:30 am, no-one picked the phone in service department and I didn't even get a response back for the voicemail I left. After persistent calling someone picked the phone and on hearing the situation I was again put on brief hold and later back on the phone line of service department which went to voicemail.
Overall the experience was really bad.
Situations like these can't be planned unlike the basic car servicing. The dealers need to be better prepared to serve the consumer in these kind of situations.< /review>

He was polite and suggested I may be asking a bit too little for my car and suggested I bring it to them and if it was what I said it was, they would buy it at my asking price.  I loaded up my wife in the car and drove down to have the manager there tell me he would offer more than 1/3 less than my offer because of a couple of things that showed up on CarFax (minor bumper damage due to being hit from behind at a stop light, not once but twice).  Why would they not have checked before calling me?  I posted the VIN with the ad.  This was a huge waste of our time and we were basically treated as 3rd class citizens when we were there.  I will NEVER do business with them.  Rick<//Text>

<user_name>Cameron Hudson<//user_name>< review>
I went here to have a software recall performed. I chose this place because it was the nearest official Toyota service center that had a fully functional (albeit barebones) online appointment system. The poor UI of the appointment system made me leery, but when I arrived, I was impressed. The customer service I received from Todd Fitzsimmons was excellent. The building is grand, and looks like it was built yesterday. I waited for the recall to be completed, and it was completed within the time estimate that they gave when I arrived (2-3 hr), about twice as fast as the estimate given to me by my local Toyota Sunnyvale (4-5 hr). I didn't have to pay anything for the recall, and there were no bogus attempts to upsell me. I'll definitely return for my next service. I'm happy with Piercey Toyota in general and Todd Fitzsimmons in particular.</review>

<resp>None< /resp><time>1530518593893< /time>< Text>
We just purchased a vehicle from Piercey Toyota. We had the best of experiences! Since we didn't want to go through the hassle of negotiating prices with the dealer, we decided to use the Costco Car Purchase program. This was very different from our experience with another dealership that we worked with before Piercey Toyota. With that dealership, they misrepresented the Costco price to us over the phone. When we got down to that dealership, they first made us wait for 40 minutes before talking to us. Then after we test drove the car, they falsely   claimed that Costco no longer have the discount for our model any more! So we have to over pay $2,500 more if we still want the car! That was ridiculous! We reported them to Costco and so didn't have high hopes when Piercey Toyota called. It felt different right from the beginning when we were contacted by Piercey's representation (Chen Zaballero). Chen informed us that they didn't have the exact model that we wanted, so he offered to order one for us and still honored the Costco price. He kept us posted throughout the whole production process and gave us a good idea when the car will be available. The day we went in to pick the car up, Chen was away and we were helped by Pari Juergens instead. Pari was most helpful indeed. There was a lot of paper work to go through and she was very patient and helpful. Since our car is a hybrid, there are also a lot of new features to cover. Pari was very knowledgeable and explained everything clearly. Then we went through the finance department. That took a bit of negotiating and went on longer than we expected but Carol Wong made the whole process fun. To our surprise, Pari was still waiting for us after we were done with the finance part. The dealership was closed by that time. Pari was still very pleasant when she delivered the car to us. Instead of hurrying us, she took the time to highlight the important parts of the different manuals to us. When we finally walked to pick up the car, she even offered to take a picture of us with our new car! All in all, it was a very pleasant car buying experience after the disappointment with the other dealership. A big thanks to everyone at Piercey Toyota.</Text>

<review>I was getting ready to drive back to the east coast so I needed an oil change. I found this dealership had the highest ratings of those nearby despite having to drive a little farther. It was worth it. I felt like I was at my home dealership. They performed the recommended mileage maintenance and since Toyota has electronic records all that information was sent to my home dealership. Next time I drive my RAV 4 across country I will definitely visit them before I drive back.
*2021 February update.
Marvin is great. Didn't realize until a month ago my auxiliary battery on hybrid RAV4 needed replacing. Bouncie made it difficult to find that alert on their (non Toyota) app, and the alert started before I drove out here. I returned to this trusted dealer's service department and so glad Marvin is my service advisor. This trip so far I've replaced the aux battery, oil change, and they're doing a full alignment. Tires were only $100 cheaper at Costco, but since I wasn't paying for them we went with Costco. If I had to do it again, I'd stick to Piercey for tires. Huge open waiting area, WiFi (password is on your work order). Right now vending machines are secured, so if you need a drink bring your own with a straw. All customers are masked and keep at least 12 feet apart. There isn't anything nearby as far as I could tell. Super easy to get to from I-880 and easy to get back on that freeway. Same exit as Great American mall, on the other side (east) of the freeway. Look forward to my next trip out here and returning here for service.< /review><pictures>None<//pictures><Response>None<//Response>< gmapID>

WELCOME TO PIERCEY TOYOTA, WE SELL USED CSR LEMONS AND MAKE OUR CUSTOMERS BUY THE GAS THEY USE FOR TEST DRIVES!!

If you are looking for a lemon buy here, Piercy sells used cars that are lemons. When I bought my used car here I expected to get a vehicle that at least would run. When I test drove it it had problems with a front tire. I asked them to fix it, I could have put Aaron at myself. When I returned to pick up the car because I trusted the company and I bought the car the tire had never been properly fixed. I had to wait for the tire to be fixed and the car wouldn't even start so I had to wait for a battery to be installed. Unacceptable service for a customer who drove from Modesto!

I didn't make it to the stop sign before the vehicle stalled. After I started the vehicle up I drove to the next stop sign and the vehicle stalled again. I could not keep the vehicle running if I came to a stop. When I finally did get to Modesto I had to drive the vehicle that I had just purchased to my own mechanic to have it worked on. Then when I returned to the Bay area I drove the car back to the dealer to complain. If you days later they have me drive the vehicle over to their mechanics shop located in the East Side of San Jose. The mechanic reeked of alcohol and was drunk, he actually fell asleep in my car when he went on a test drive. This was the mechanic that would be working on my vehicle, he never managed to totally fix the problems and as a result, the broken down vehicle I purchase sits across the street from the dealership in a parking lot.

This is the only car lot that I have ever been to where I was told that I had to buy the gas if I wanted to do a test drive. The dealer told me that they would not repossess the vehicle because it wasn't worth it. Nor would Piercy accept the vehicle on trade in for a  new car or even a used car.

If you want to buy a used vehicle from a dealership that does not take care of their customers, HAS DRUNK MECHANICS WORKING ON YOUR VEHICLE THEN BUY HERE!

<text>Ripping off customers - women car owners should go elsewhere. I came in to help with an issue on my mother's car's radio unit, explained the diagnostics and attempts I had made to fix it. They seemed bored and handed us off to the one female salesperson, where I was assured that they would run complete diagnostics on it and see if it could be fixed. Shame on me, I didn't make them explain exactly what "run diagnostics" involved - when I returned 4 hours later, I was told that yes, in fact, there was an error message being displayed on my screen, and they recommended I spend $600 to replace the entire unit. No attempt to say even what that error message meant. When I asked the salesperson sitting at his desk (2nd desk over from the entry door - stay away!) he first tried to pass me off to the female rep again, swore when he found out she was on break (he was sitting and texting on his phone when I came up), pretended to look at his screen (which was displaying another customer's bill - I could see it) and said it meant the CD was stuck (which is what I had told them when I first brought the car in, and which was the only thing printed on my receipt). He then slipped and said that they couldn't actually go in and look at anything in the unit because if they caused more damage to the unit Toyota would be responsible for replacing it - and recommended I go to a non-Toyota store to run the same "diagnostics" that I had supposedly just paid this place for.
So, they charged $76 to push the same buttons I had already been through (and told them I had been through) to display an error message. And after investigating the error message myself - it does not just mean "cd is stuck" (I am not a complete idiot thank you), it indicates an error in the changer mechanism, a common problem in Toyota cars, and if my mother had spent $600 to replace it with the same unit she would likely have just had the same issue in the future.
$76 and 4 hours to figure out the problem myself.
I will be going elsewhere in the future, and encourage others to do the same. I should not have trusted that a Toyota dealer automatically meant honest service, or not attempting to rip off female customers.< /text>< Date>

< Time>
1414465832093</Time>
<Rate>4<//Rate>< text>
I bought my previously-owned Camry Hybrid from Piercey Toyota in 2010. Since I had an extended warranty on the vehicle, I was reluctant to bring it to a non-dealer shop for maintenance, even though my experience with previous dealers has not been great. But Piercey Toyota has never let me down. I bring my car in for regular oil changes every 5000 miles, and let them do any required maintenance as needed. The advisers there are friendly, and tell me when I should or shouldn't bother to have certain maintenance done. Warranty-covered issues have mostly been handled well (just one snag once that turned out in my favor). I also bring my car in first thing, and wait comfortably while working with the free wifi until my car is ready. On the occasions when I did need a lift to my office nearby, their shuttle was relatively fast and efficient with drop-off.< /text>

<Text>Ripping off customers - women car owners should go elsewhere. I came in to help with an issue on my mother's car's radio unit, explained the diagnostics and attempts I had made to fix it. Shame on me, I didn't make them explain exactly what "run diagnostics" involved - when I returned 4 hours later, I was told that yes, in fact, there was an error message being displayed on my screen, and they recommended I spend $600 to replace the entire unit. No attempt to say even what that error message meant. When I asked the salesperson sitting at his desk (2nd desk over from the entry door - stay away!) he first tried to pass me off to the female rep again, swore when he found out she was on break (he was sitting and texting on his phone when I came up), pretended to look at his screen (which was displaying another customer's bill - I could see it) and said it meant the CD was stuck (which is what I had told them when I first brought the car in, and which was the only thing printed on my receipt). He then slipped and said that they couldn't actually go in and look at anything in the unit because if they caused more damage to the unit Toyota would be responsible for replacing it - and recommended I go to a non-Toyota store to run the same "diagnostics" that I had supposedly just paid this place for.
So, they charged $76 to push the same buttons I had already been through (and told them I had been through) to display an error message. And after investigating the error message myself - it does not just mean "cd is stuck" (I am not a complete idiot thank you), it indicates an error in the changer mechanism, a common problem in Toyota cars, and if my mother had spent $600 to replace it with the same unit she would likely have just had the same issue in the future.
$76 and 4 hours to figure out the problem myself.
I will be going elsewhere in the future, and encourage others to do the same. I should not have trusted that a Toyota dealer automatically meant honest service, or not attempting to rip off female customers.< /Text>< Pics>

<rate>4</rate>< Text>
Went to purchase a Toyota SUV & bought the Rav 4 LE FWD at this Dealership. Pratik was the Sales Rep who received and took me to a Test Drive (though he was more eager to get me buy the Car the same day). His Manager Ed was more calm and realistic and gave us reasonable quotes and options for me to choose from which made me come back to them next day so that I can buy the Car. Pratik didnt specify about any Corporate Discounts/deals  or even the Costco Discount which was available for Costco Members until I asked about it the next after a quote from the same Dealership.  I went back to Ed/Pratik (because Ed was talking very well and outspoken about what we/him wanted). Pratik was good in his explanation when he mentioned about the Car Features during Delivery. The one thing which I disliked about was the way Pratik kept on coming back at us when we were discussing which Car to buy (either the LE FWD/AWD or XLE etc)  and asking how long we will take. This was my first car Purchase and I didnt want to do it in a hurry which even Ed accepted but this action was little annoying considering any first time buyer would definitely have the confusion about what to choose from etc, which if they take care in future will help them move to the next Level in Customer Satisfaction. Oh I missed to tell about the Finance Dept Lady Mia who was very nice and talkative discussed many things and was equally as good as Ed. She helped us in what are available Options for a Customer/Costco Members etc and gave us a very good deal with the repair warranty and Tire Warranty eventhough the Paper work took us more than 2 hours to get done. Pratik seemed to show urgency in the whole process while he was talking the first day as well as next. If you remove the urgency and show little patience will take you places. Another reason for  reducing it to a 4 Star instead of the 5 was the Final Key Delivery point which I believe every Dealership will try to impress the Customer with the way they either dont give any Keychain along with Car Key or rather give a small one which has the Dealership name on it. Instead I got a Paper Clip type (see pic) which actually had cut my fingers twice before I left the place. I atleast expected a better send off to top off an ever lasting Impression with Piercey Toyota @Milpitas.< /Text>

< text>
Great service. I was told on the phone that if I showed up before noon without an appointment, they could probably fix my problem. I arrived around 9:30 and asked for my favorite Service Agent - Hong. She understood the problem and arranged for a ride to take me home. In the afternoon she called with the diagnosed problem and the estimate. When it was fixed, she called and arranged for a ride to pick me up. I had the car and was home by 3pm!

<rate>1</rate><Review>I just purchased a vehicle here. Be very very careful of the finance folks. It's where they make their money. Lots of forms to sign and they will push hard for you to buy gap insurance, protection plan, and warranty. They even go as far as changing the toyota APR {reducing the APR) in order to "adjust" the amount available to purchase these protection plan, supposedly at no additional cost to you. Yes there is a cost to you, because if you want to pay your car off early or do a trade in or sell it off...the payoff amount is different than the original toyota APR provided by toyota.  Not sure if this is even legal -- it is a tricky way to get you to purchase the various protection plans. Be very careful.</Review>< pics>

I phoned back and was told to drive there to make an appointment for recall, vehicle must be inspected by mechanic 1st visit, after that they would schedule 2nd visit if recall work proved to be needed. So I left work right away and arrived at noon only to find all four lanes entirely blocked with cars both directions, was afraid I would not get back to work by 2PM meeting time. Asked how long such a line takes, was told not long. Got in line, but when one car was cleared and all others re-started their cars and pulled forward one car length, I left a little room to be certain that I could leave if necessary, there were none behind me so I did not affect others.  I walked in to service area and everyone ignored me.  Half an hour later, I was the dead last customer with vehicle, Piercey guy comes out, walks right by me, takes my keys out of ignition, proceeds to take my keys off my key ring, never making eye contact.  I asked if we should not come to an agreement on terms before taking my vehicle keys. I had my Yaris serviced by them until 2012.  Their facility is awesome!  Their people are very attentive and responsive to my wants and needs.
